text: ok so now i understand a little bit more. what we need to teach young men, which is something neither the police nor the principal at nova high mentioned at the discipline assemblies, is that respecting other people's bodies, valuing consent, treating women as equals, and having self-control isn't just something you do to stay out of trouble; it's something that makes you a better person, instead of some disgusting misogynist. but no, they would rather talk about the legal implications of sharing nudes from underage girls, as if the morality of not doing things like that didn't matter. however, while boys aren't taught to not rape, they think it's ok to teach girls to dress a certain way or act a certain way to avoid sexual assault. but what can you expect from a man who lacks so much self-control that he gets drunk at a high school prom, when he's supposed to be the example, and a man who think it's acceptable to lie and make false allegations about his subordinates whenever he feels like they piss him off. good thing those records haven't gone away. he's not the only one i'm fighting, however. any person who permits this senseless rape culture is automatically my enemy. this is personal to me and my family members. #metoo

text:
letâ€™s clear up some things about human trafficking- 
please look at these numbers about human trafficking. 
many people have no idea that human trafficking is more than sex trafficking and that the majority of human trafficking is nonsexual forced labor.
youâ€™ve probably seen me talk about the conflation between sex work and sex trafficking. and this is one of the many reasons why thatâ€™s a dangerous misconception. when is the last time you heard about an initiative to help trafficked workers in other industries? 
laws introduced to help those who are sex trafficked often do nothing of the sort (reports point to fosta as making it harder to track down victims!!). instead, they harm consensual sex workers. and, *bonus*, censor women. 
i know i focus a lot of my talking points around sex work, and i want yâ€™all to know itâ€™s about a lot more than that. 
sex trafficking has become an easy way for politicians to push modesty and misogynistic agendas.
the portrait of a young woman being trafficked for sex is sensational. it paints an atrocious picture thatâ€™s easy to use to motivate people to back laws they donâ€™t even understand.
remember when all the platforms changes their terms of service and those changes ended up with more restrictions against women (remember when #malestripper was ok but regular #stripper was blocked?)
to round this out with one more point (i could do this forever): people on both ends of the political spectrum get wrapped up in sex trafficking rhetoric. people get very upset and ready to pass laws because these womenâ€™s bodies are being used against their will....
yet, when we talk about how 20% of women in the us are raped, when me talk about #metoo, when we talk about sex workers being silenced and murdered, when we talk about the marginalization of woc, who the fuck is passing laws to help us?

text:
friday 3.8.19 | 7-10pm
celebrate international womenâ€™s day with us! join us for the opening reception of female gaze, featuring 19 local artists. our space will be action packed that night with â€œfemale gazeâ€ in the main gallery, @theresiduecollectiveâ€™s â€œlolita, go homeâ€ in the perimeter gallery, and @femmefrequencies in the theater. cash bar, free parking, really cool staff... bring your friends! flyer photo by the talented @dog_god24 
female gaze:
under our current administration, and in the #metoo and timeâ€™s up era, what does this mean for how art is made and exhibited, by whom and for what audience? do we recognize this male gaze, reject it, change it, dissolve it? does it even still exist as a binary gender-based perspective, or has it evolved to signify any imbalance of power and agency? who defines the term, the viewer, or the viewed?

art share l.a.â€™s female gaze presents our experience as females, femme-identifying, non-binary, and ally communities in 2019 by staging a public forum for an on ongoing dialogue. what does the world look like through our gaze? and how that inevitably influences our creative practice. #artsharela #femalegaze

text:
8 out of 10 (as reported by @rainn, see link in profile). this, this 80%, is where rape culture lives, festers, thrives.
this is where victim shaming and blaming and self-blaming are ingrained. 
this is what were they wearing, how much did they drink, who where they with, what did they think would happen when they went to that party, when they owned a toy, when they went about their lives?
this is where entitlement and privilege and objectification breed, where stereotypes about gender and sexuality and race and ability and size batter, where agency is not a given, where humans are devalued.
this is in no way to devalue the 20% of instances where the perpetrator was a stranger. not one bit. all of these things happen there â€“ hell, itâ€™s why so many of us live in a state of hypervigilance, fearful in broad daylight, keys poking between our fingers, altering our routes, our routines.
but this notion that we are objects, things that exist to satisfy othersâ€™ whims, lesser-thanâ€¦ itâ€™s perpetuated, permitted in that 80%, built into songs and movies and novels and the fabric of our society. 
this is the discussion i will continue to have, with my children, with my family, with my friends, with my colleagues, with anyone who asks about this work or opens a conversational door. âœ’ğŸ–¤@thewordforthis

text:
i don't think love ever set me free, or any truth ever did, but at the same time i don't think it was love or the truth either.
it felt more sincere. something i could feel deep in the cells of my tissue
so, what's real really? is it fear, is it me, is it  them and their opinion? emotions? am i steered? i can't tell you nearly enough, but i know that i am fucked by default, with loose shifting perspectives and moodswings way out of beeing practicable.
 i still get up every day and don't really want to brag about it, but i guess the time has come to open up to the world and talk about all the shit that happened and let new shit happen. i mean, if i offend you, good. that's progression, cause you can then reflect why you got offended and dont give a shit the next time in.
i just don't feel the urge, cause people really dont deserve any of this. neither positives nor negatives
and that's probably just my muscle memory, cause i got treated shitty by people who think they are witty like a trillion times, disrespected, overheared
then listened to, my jokes used for their own lines... forgotten in rooms, at home, nobody noticed that i on parties was gone to cry in a corner. 
the world was never fair, neither it says in any book, only order says it is in a chaotic form, but you can not cheat and steal while at the same time throwing tantrums on a crook. that's basically a blackhole, consuming itself in a loop.

great, i sound like a depressed coldbrewed coffee tastes.
well yeah, i got major depression since i'm a kid. but i don't like how #metoo spreads dumbness instead of awareness. so, #mewto cause fuck your victimization. i better give you aids.

text:
the hashtag #thingsdisabledpeopleknow has gone viral in recent weeks.
started in america by blogger imani barbarin, it's got tweeters from all corners of the disability community and globe sharing those annoyances disabled people experience, but which might never occur to anyone else.
imani has spoken to bbc about why she started it, why guide dog owner damon thinks people break wind in his presence and whether this could be a #metoo moment for the disability community.

cw: sexual assault

today marks exactly two years since i was sexually assaulted. iâ€™m posting this not to gain sympathy or attention, but to hopefully inspire someone who went through something similar to me and to help them heal. instagram is often a highlight of the best times of your life, and that isnâ€™t real. i wanted to be honest with you all and show how iâ€™ve grown from my assault. at the time, i was in the second semester of my freshman year of college. i was lonely, chasing after boys who were never going to like me, and found myself in a situation in which an older guy violated my trust and my body. the worst part was being under the influence and not being fully aware of what was happening to me. i remember leaving his bedroom multiple times to use the bathroom in an attempt to contact my floor mates, but it was the middle of the night and i didnâ€™t have any cell service. i remember my whole body being chaffed by his scruffy beard. but most of all, i remember finally getting home, getting immediately in the shower and just shaking. i sat in the dorm hallway rocking back and forth while reporting my assault to campus authorities until the ras made me go to my room. 
i did everything right. i reported, i told my friends, and eventually my family. but i never got justice and iâ€™m still recovering today. but not every survivor is able to do that, whether it be due to victim shaming, potential repercussions, or not having proper evidence. if i could ask just one thing from all of you reading this, it would be this: when you see news stories surface of sexual violence from years ago or hear that your friends have suffered but didnâ€™t know how to or want to come forward, donâ€™t question their credibility. believe them. we are all survivors, coping in our own way at our own pace. and it was not our fault.

if you or someone you know has experienced sexual abuse, call rainnâ€™s free 24/7 confidential hotline at 1-800-656-4673 or visit hotline.rainn.org.

text:
#justbe, #woman

on the cusp of womenâ€™s history month, i have to say how grateful i am: to those who have sacrificed and continue to throw their reputations, rights and lives on the line for us to live better, liberated lives.

from the suffragettes to rosa parks, michelle obama and aoc; to madonna, the spice girls, lady gaga, and everyone fighting the #metoo and #timesup movements - this is just the beginning. 
to whomever inspired you and led you to believe that you, woman, are whole, wonderful and wise, we are indebted. 
donâ€™t be what they tell you to be. laugh heartily, if you so wish. live meekly or outlandishly. donâ€™t care for fashion or wear an unmissable red lip every day. do you. be you, authentically you. and lift others up. understanding and respect will only propel us forwards. ğŸ’«

text_retweet:
i've set some new goals and dreams for the fall of this year and right away i have been feeling completely overwhelmed. 
some people can look at things and easily break them down into small, manageable chunks. i have #adhd so that is difficult for me to do. 
not impossible, difficult. 
i know i can do difficult things. 
what strategy do i use? 
these days i am trying out #compassion. noticing that i am doing a lot right now. i want to have my plans all down now. but, planning is exhausting. 
i explain to myself that setting a planning date to plan for a few months from now isn't #procrastionation it's #timemanagement. 
you're allowed to plan to plan. you're allowed to work within your capacity.

she was kind enough to film a guest spot for the upcoming finale of being mary jane. between takes, it was both of us talking and strategizing, venting and celebrating. you want a leader who truly believes in inclusivity. for tarana, itâ€™s not about personal gain or attention but doing the work in a way that makes people feel like they can join in. when youâ€™ve been sidelined for so long, itâ€™s exhilarating to know that such a powerful voice is finally breaking through. tarana will continue to do this work, but the stage will be bigger and the microphone turned all the way up. she will inspire legislation and new crops of voters. she will sway old voters. she will open eyes. sheâ€™s not even going to bring more seats to the tableâ€”sheâ€™s going to turn the table over and build a new one.â€ @time

text:
as black history month comes to a close, we honor tireless, courageous, inspiring leaders, activists, artists, writers and transformational voices like shirley chisholm, byllye avery, flo kennedy, yamani hernandez, and many, many others. we owe them so very much.

we must continue to work in partnership and allyship. the situation is still so dire for so many. just this month, trump is dismantling title x for family planning programs, which supports funding for the healthcare of 4 million people--mostly low-income and people of color. it states that nowhere that refers patients for an abortion (or informs them of the full extent of their options) is eligible for this funding.

oppression and disenfranchisement take many forms. one of them is withholding funding, and eliminating informed consent. the #prochoicenation will not rest until no body is a battleground.

the 26-year-old was accused of forcibly raping a woman in 2016, after a night of drinking at a waco, texas bar. 
the woman accused testified that she'd been drinking and was intoxicated when oakman assaulted her. she said she told oakman that she wanted to leave his duplex that night but he wouldn't allow it.
oakman's attorney told jurors that the sex was consensual. fortunately, most of the physical evidence was in oakman's favor. during the hearing, the defense called richard donald conner, a digital forensics expert, as its final witness. conner said text messages inviting oakman to the bar were deleted from the accuserâ€™s phone.
oakman was facing up to 20 years in prison if convicted. his case, among many others are examples that he say/she say accusations will ruin an athlete's career. and in the "me too" era, it has become more common. after oakman's arrest on the sexual assault charge, which occurred only two weeks before the 2016 nfl draft, he went undrafted. and his nfl career derailed. november 2017, oakman signed with theÂ triangle torchÂ of theÂ american arena leagueÂ for the 2018 season. however, he has been american football defensive end for the bismarck bucks of champions indoor football since the 2018 season began. i'm hoping that this young man will get a second chance. â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ â€¢

text: as a writer i want to be honest, as a human i want to be vulnerable. my book is me, it is my story and iâ€™m owning that! today a lot came up, a lot kind of hit me all at once and iâ€™m digesting it. i was assaulted last year, i didnâ€™t realize that that happened till months later and iâ€™m still processing through it. let me tell you, your healing process, your journey is not meant to be based on anyone else but you. things are triggering. things will come up at times you donâ€™t even think they will come up. iâ€™m sharing my story because, when it happened i didnâ€™t know how to say no... i didnâ€™t know if i could i didnâ€™t know what would happen if i did. i was so broken and so lost at this point in my life that it made sense. iâ€™m not going into detail because a lot of it is shared in my book, but since iâ€™ve been open with my story i have heard of many others who have been hurt and stayed silent or spoke and havenâ€™t been believed and i just want you to know you are not alone. healing is hard, but you are loved. and there is support out there. emotions will come. triggers will be there, but i have found solace in good counseling and god. my identity in christ is everything, because iâ€™m nothing without it. i donâ€™t know if anyone needed to hear that but iâ€™m here to change the game, to be myself, and to open up about where i come from. without god, i would still be in the darkest hole of my life. but iâ€™m here today to say that although hard times come, there is light out there, there are good people out there, and the love god gives is far above anything i have ever experienced. i pray for anyone who is broken tonight, and feeling alone. god has you and this is not your end! just as it isnâ€™t mine! #metoo #youarenotalone #fight #speakup #writerscommunity #createimpact #bodypositivitymovement #influencer #writerscommunity #vulnerability #changethegame #godlovesyou #survivor #beatingthis #movingon #better

text:
#ohoreads you know you want this, kristen roupenian's debut short story collection. "the truth was that if a woman bit a man in an office environment, there would be a strong assumption that the man had done something to deserve it."
.
roupenian shot to fame after her story cat person, about an ambiguously bad date, went viral. you can't come into this expecting more witty takes on millennial dating, however - with the exception of stories like the good guy, from the perspective of a man who has unironically weaponised the friendzone, most of these are straight-up body horror. think melded flesh, crunching cheekbones and ocular violation. it's an uneven collection, but i appreciate that it does delve into problematic spaces where women are just as much the aggressors as men, if not more so. there are particular delights like biter, a sly twist on #metoo, in which a woman fantasises about biting her attractive male co-worker. link in bio to an author interview (paywalled) and a review (not!) #lookinglit
.

.

text:
every new level demands a new version of you.

want different results? try making different choices. try doing something different. i've learned that i dont slay all my giants, and then my life isÂ problem free. nope. as i choose to level up in my life, new challenges and struggles arise. i guess that's really the definition of growth.

i'm going through some growing pains right now. they hurt. they are scary. they require faith. the moments i can see through the fears and unknowns, it's really exciting. god's walking me through this growth so i can be prepared for a new season.

hold onto hope during your own growing pains.

text:
the favourite
.
â–« address: yorgos lanthimos.
cast: olivia colman, emma stone, rachel weisz, nicholas hoult, joe alwyn, james smith, mark gatiss
title in v.o: the favorite
acionalnationality: united kingdom
â–« year: 2018 â–«date release: 01-18-2019 â–«gender: comedy dramatic
â–«management: deborah davis, tony mcnamara photography: robbie ryan
â¡ synopsis: early eighteenth century. england is at war with the french. a weakened queen, anne (olivia colman), occupies the throne, while her friend lady sarah (rachel weisz) governs the country instead, due to the precarious state of health and the unstable character of the monarch. when a new maid appears, abigail (emma stone), her charm seduces sarah. sarah helps abigail and she has an opportunity to return to her aristocratic roots. as politics occupies much of sarah's time, abigail begins to accompany the queen more often. you will develop a friendship that you will use to satisfy your ambitions.
âœ” the best: olivia colman, spectacular, and the bad grape of the whole.
âœ” worse yet: that the detractors of lanthimos think that at least oscar marketing has been sold.
if it were not, because the favorite has been boiling for years in the greek kitchen of yorgos lanthimos, for the first time as her usual scriptwriter, i have to applaud her for her timely editing on stage.
in the era of #metoo, this elizabethan tragicomedy, which gives itself to the historical anachronism with the aggressive freedom of a parody of monty python, which twists its viperine tongue in the words and the english verb in the same way as the old man in the future lace and the miracle, the extraordinary olivia colman, the carnival of matrices and contradictions, miraculously, converge in a moving humanity, with great angles that rewrite the influence of kubrick in the work of the director of canino, presents a love triangle in the word that is explained through the exercise of power.
.
.

text:
all survivors need to be listened to. congressman @repjimjordan needs to be held accountable for his inaction, for his silence. he was either willfully negligent by ignoring his students who spoke to him about the abuse, or he is the most oblivious man to ever walk this earth. but, he does not get to pass judgment on one man for being dishonest while intimidating the men he failed so terribly.

we are demanding the house ethics committee look into whether or not jim jordan knew about and protected a serial molester and if he used his position as a congressman to intimidate survivors on fox news and to have them write statements of support for his denials.

text:
thrilled to welcome shelley bolton - the social entrepreneur behind the downtown-eastside's "east van roasters" to the panel for this year's women's awareness week for #iwd2019 in vancouver. .
.
n 2011, enticed by the challenge of bean-to-bar chocolate making and coffee roasting, shelley was recruited as director of social enterprise for the phs community services society to launch two employment programs for local women - the window community art shop and east van roasters. these programs are socially conscious businesses providing a compassionate work environment for women facing challenges in their lives. shelley is inspired every day by the dynamic and tenacious team of women she works alongside within the magical world of creating delicious and nourishing food.
.
. 
the well beings & weekend rituals (march 4, 9 & 10)

text: part 1 - yesterday was the 3rd anniversary of taking fv to report her sexual assault to the @irvinepolice .  5.5hrs waiting outside the room while she told the cop what happened; they didnâ€™t even offer a female cop to be in the room. ofcr jesse busta was polite, but the questions he asked kept implying it was her fault. i will make a special post about him later. his report, given to us just as the sol expired, read like a bad date where she was a willing participant. busta refused to talk to ken, refused to request to see kenâ€™s phone for the video he took, and refused to allow a context call. she even mentioned she was willing to go to jail if they could show she was making a false claim. i begged for any help. i had promised her the cops would do the right thing and they made me a liar. busta said since no witness to rape and no witness to creation of video of rape then there was no rape. in his words, â€œi see no crime here.â€ their complete disregard for what ken ward did actually ended up causing as much damage as what ken did. ken is an animal and behaved like it, but we were raised to believe cops were the heroes. busta even said, â€œyou watch too many movies,â€ in regards to our expectations. we know convictions are near impossible, but seeing the cops take any action could have helped her sense of self worth and safety; the law didnâ€™t care. i hope every city employee that ignored her suffers with a loved one what i have suffered: futility, frustration, absolute hate, and loss of faith in the system. only then will they learn to help the ones in need. later, we drove through newport and found a new restaurant to eat and try to console each other. #rape #metoo #copfail #irvinepd #kennethdward #corestrategycorp #vonkarmantowers #limpdickrapist #woodbridgeirvine #cresapartnersforthewin #kenworkedatcresa #kenward #coerciverapeisrape #outtherapists #overthemoon #lds #mormonprobs #cresaglobal #cresanewportbeach

text:
today is the 100th anniversary of the march 1st movement, also known as 3.1 movement, which was a mass demonstration of korean resistance against japan's colonization. it's been 74 years since liberation, and there are still wounds yet to be healed.
.
japanse imperialism in asia was just as terrible as nazism in europe. they slaughtered and tortured more than 5 million koreans, forced women and girls into horrible sexual enslavement, and forced men into ruthless labor.
.

text:
the doorway to self discovery. .
.
i had the honor and privilege of spending a few days at this incredibly magical place. i entered these doors believing that i had done most of the real â€œhardâ€ inner self work in the past already, and that this trip would be focusing on refining myself, clearing out attachments, letting go of residual â€œstuffâ€ that i was already aware of and consciously working on. i thought i had done so much digging into the shadows of myself in the past that there couldnâ€™t possibly be anything really â€œnewâ€ to discover. wow. i was wrong! .
.
no matter how many things i uncover, it seems thereâ€™s always another layer to peel back. i used to feel discouraged by that, but now i see it as a beautiful endless gift. what intricate and perfectly crafted being we are. we often see ourselves, our minds, our bodies, as â€œmessed upâ€ or â€œbrokenâ€ but they are working exactly as designed, alerting us to imbalances and sending signals for us to recalibrate, run a systems check, and correct the imbalance. when we are connected, we notice these signals. itâ€™s important to take time to connect consciously, to tune in, listen deeply, and work to recalibrate to a central point within ourselves. it doesnâ€™t have to be at a retreat, though. it can be done any time, any place, at any age. .
.
it will be a process of integration now. remembering my lessons, working them into my daily life, constantly checking in with how all thatâ€™s feeling and presenting. while i work with this, tell me... how are you connecting? .
.

text:
we have exciting femme cabal book club news! lots of info to share here, so buckle in for the ride:

our first ever book club meeting was a huge success! we had 13 attendees, all of whom had read the book and actively engaged in conversation about the plot and its real world meaning. it was super nerdy and super fun.

we are going to host femme cabal book club on a bimonthly basis (6 per year). the next meeting will be on tuesday, april 16th at 7 pm at the barking buffalo cafe. 
our next book is "educated" by tara westover, a "stunning memoir about family, loss and the struggle for a better future." check out our website to learn more about book club via the link in our bio. 
who can come? everyone. but space is limited so rsvp asap! 
rsvp via the direct link in our bio. â€”
~~~~~~~~~~~ we will be sharing book club information on our brand new facebook group. join it if you are interested in participating in book club: search for â€œfemme cabal book clubâ€ and request to join.

text:
.
.
us
.
i'll never stop
because i tell their stories.
because my story belongs
to them as much as it does to me.
it belongs to us.
.
maybe it's not your story,
maybe not yet, because
"these things happen"
to so many of us.
.
you know us,
your sisters, friends,
mothers, but also,
brothers and fathers.
you know us.
.
we are the ones who
don't hurt others,
don't take what isn't
and never was, ours.
you know, us.
.
we never wanted
to have them talk to us like that,
to have our humanity
stripped away
even when our clothes weren't
just because they thought
they knew "people like us".
.
but when we are naked,
when that's our story,
we can't shake the feeling
we're bare to the nerves for so long after
those we gave our hearts to
"knew" us.
.
so i talk, write, speak up,
for them, for us.
and i'll never stop
because i know them, and
you
know
us.
.
.
*"us." for years i had pinned to my driver's side visor, "raise your voice, even if it's shaking." i'll never stop telling my truth because my truth belongs to so many of us.
.

// lack of a structured mindset is like not wearing foundation but wearing dramatic eyes and lips. (unless you got the skin for it. and if you do, you're super privilaged idc) some people, like myself, had to work on that shit and figure out why my face was beginning to look like a cobble stone road. life ain't fair but at least i learn to fix my problems, move on, and help others with my knowledge and experience. cause, as a body waxer, i can say i've noticed a lot of girls with inherently great skin that dont know how to take care of the rest of their largest organ. (and if you do, your 40 year old self will appreciate it). but yeah. we all have different kinds of skin that we hide underneath makeup but there's only so much scarring you can cover. cause your makeup looks the best when your skin looks and feels its best. so once your mind has some structure, everything else will fall into place. kinda like tetris though--i repeat-- life is not fair. 
#esthetician #metoo

text:
a texas jury has found former baylor defensive end shawn oakman not guilty of raping another student in 2016.
the mclennan county jury deliberated about two hours in waco on thursday before acquitting the 26-year-old oakman of sexual assault.
the woman who says she was raped testified earlier that she'd been drinking and was intoxicated when oakman assaulted her. she said she told oakman that she wanted to leave his duplex that night but he wouldn't allow it.
oakman's attorney told jurors that the two wanted to be together that night and that they had consensual sex. the two had a previous relationship. #shawnoakman #bayloruniversity #metoo #dontruinmylife

text:
feminism:

original term:

feminism is a political ideology and series of movements that seek the equal rights for men and women. feminism started off originally as a movement that sought equality of opportunities and equality in general for women and men in the society, workplace etc. i personally definitely agree with the original definition of feminism as iâ€™m sure most people do too. but over time, feminism has changed into the third wave which completely demeans and destroys the sanctity and legitimacy of the original movement which i will get into later. initially feminism started off with women demanding equal voting rights and has since risen to popularity in the west. i sincerely wish feminism goes back to being what it truly was, as anyone thatâ€™s a feminist now canâ€™t be taken seriously as this movement has lost its true purpose and focuses more on man hating. as iâ€™ve established, iâ€™m a believer in the original term of feminism.

third wave:

the third wave of feminism is the new form that feminism has â€œevolvedâ€ into over the past few years with the growth of the #metoo movement. in my opinion, the third wave of feminism is disgusting as it focuses on man hating and is a very dark, vindictive, hateful form of feminism. the third wave feminists especially in the west have sough to generalise all men as dangerous and hateful. i personally hate this form of feminism as it does nothing but demean the character of men. a lot of women when asked if theyâ€™re third wave feminists conveniently say they only believe in the original term which is unfair. a lot of these feminists show their support towards the third wave in policy beliefs but use the â€œi believe in the original termâ€ to avoid arguments and criticism. i hope the third wave of feminism ends for the betterment of humanity.

text:
feminism:

gender wage gap:

the gender wage gap is a myth. no established economist would seriously consider the gender wage gap. the problem is, most people vaguely compare the total earnings of men and women and generalise it to saying that there is a wage gap. other factors like the total working hours, maternity leave etc. arenâ€™t considered. if these other factors are considered then men and women are paid equally for the amount of work that they do. instead of focusing on myths like this, women in the west should focus on equality for women in the middle east or in rural areas as these are the areas that really require the use of feminism. feminists should use their voice and their resources to establish equality for the underprivileged and not to promote ridiculous ideas like the wage gap.

#metoo:

the #metoo movement started off as a social media movement of women accusing men of sexual harassment online. it initially provided women with a platform to tell their story. but as usual, it has turned into a bunch of false accusations against successful men. it really is disappointing when women come up with sexual harassment stories from about 10-20 years ago. in my opinion, a woman should be imprisoned for falsely accusing a man with sexual harassment as it demeans the character of these men who were falsely accused and goes on to ruin their careers. the #metoo movement too has lost all its originality and legitimacy as it has turned into a ridiculous movement due to radical feminists.

feminism should be about equal rights and nothing more. i might be young but that does not mean i donâ€™t understand the truth about certain ideologies and movements. i sincerely hope the feminists reading this will take into consideration what i just said and try and make the feminist movement what it truly stands for. that way everyone could be privileged to call themselves a feminist.

text:
to kickoff womenâ€™s herstory month weâ€™re excited to announce the first #thisisjane storytellers series! 
featuring 5 #womxn from diverse backgrounds, each with an equally courageous story to tell, #thisisjane is bound to be an insightful journey into the lives of everyday womxn negotiating an array of trauma(s) with the help of plant medicine. â €
â €
what occurred at the first event this week speaks to the power in unapologetic womxn facing extreme circumstances with our dear friend, jane, and why this body of work needs to be created.
â €
our why: â €
the silence surrounding violence against womxn needs to end. we believe that cannabis can be both a bridge and a vessel in ending that silence. â €
â €
she helps the sexual-assault survivor find her words. she helps the little girl who lost her mom at 10, negotiate a lonely and obsessive world into her thirties. she helped the violent crime survivor leave her house again. â €
â €
so we tell our stories not only in homage to our personal & collective healing via plant medicine, but also to end the stigma against discussing the horrific things that happen to womxn all over this world every day. â €
â €
would you share yours? â €
â €
everyday for the next 2 weeks we will be posting a different janeâ€™s trauma & healing anecdote to support the mission of this project.â €
â €
in gratitude,â €
#tijcrew â €
â €
-stay tuned! â €

text:
national state of emergency

http://www.gofundme.com/becomeempowered

thank you to everyone who has donated so far, we have almost hit Â£400 of our Â£1000 goal!

deadline this sunday 3rd march - that gives time to transfer money to freetown with enough time to pay for everything

every Â£10 donation is a school girl in sierra leone having access to travel, food and training at our 1 day event designed around women's empowerment.

training will cover education, health, self esteem and entrepreneurship in response to the hands off our girls campaign by the first lady, and the #nationalstateofemergency of #genderbasedviolence and #rape in sierra leone, recently announced by the president.

we're doing a #gofundme campaign to launch this #becomeempowered #womensempowerment event in partnership with the patriotic advocacy network in freetown sierra leone on #internationalwomensday - 8th march.

we're trying to reach 100 girls (capacity for the venue) from different schools around freetown to let them know we see them, we're behind them, and we want to practically help by empowering them with the tools to create physical, mental and emotional action and support groups in their communities

please share with your communities

text:
#femalefilmmakerfriday setiap hari jumat diperingati sebagai jumat sineas perempuan dan pekan pertama ini yang akan menjadi sorotan kita adalah seorang filmmaker yang juga aktris asal sacramento, amerika serikat, greta gerwig.
.
.
mengawali kariernya sejak tahun 2006 dengan bermain di film lol, gerwig disebut-sebut sebagai sosok yang mampu menentang gagasan gagasan sinematik pada umumnya. selain piawai dalam berakting, kemampuan gerwig dalam membuat film patut diacungi jempol, hal itu dibuktikan oleh film pertamanya yang berjudul â€˜lady birdâ€™ yang rilis pada tahun 2017 dan mendapatkan banyak pujian, bahkan membawanya pada tiga nominasi academy award, yaitu best original screenplay, best director dan best picture dan lady bird juga berhasil membawa pulang piala golden globe award untuk kategori best motion picture in musical or comedy
.
.
dan di tahun ini rencananya greta gerwig akan merilis film â€˜little womenâ€™ yang diadaptasi dari novel berjudul sama karya louisa may alcott
.
.
kira-kira sobat setara udah pada nonton lady bird belum dan apa film greta gerwig yang jadi favorit sobat setara?

text:
hoi allemaal, dit ben ik, kathelijn (maar zeg alsjeblieft maar gewoon kat). voordat ik begin wil ik alvast zeggen dat mijn taalgebruik nogal ver-engels-ed(?) is, alhoewel ik het wel leuk vind om sarcastische of hele lange zinnen volledig in het nederlands te zeggen/schrijven. dus dat kun je soms (nogal vaak) tegen gaan komen.

dat gezegd hebbende, vandaag gaan we het gezellig over mij hebben (yay). wie is "mij" dan? nou, ik ben dus kathelijn (kat). en in deze foto's zien we mij (surprise!). in de eerste foto mij nu, de tweede is van zo'n 2 maanden geleden toen ik mijn haar net geverfd had en het er nog wel goed uit zag. gelukkig ga ik het binnenkort weer verven. welke kleur zien we binnenkort. .-. ik ben net 17 en doe ook mee aan slet: de voorstelling. een project waar ik heel veel zin in heb, omdat ik het gevoel heb dat ik eindelijk eens iets doe tegen hoe oneerlijk de wereld kan zijn (ik word nu al filosofisch... oops). ik houd van muziek, toneel, tekenen, eigenlijk alle kunstvormen wel. mijn favoriete genres voor films en series zijn fantasy, horror en sci-fi. mijn favoriete genres voor muziek zijn rock, indie, punk en metal (en nog een heleboel subgenres). en mijn favoriete schrijver is michael grant (de gone-serie en de bzrk-serie zijn het echt waard om ten minste te proberen!). dat dus. tot bij de voorstelling:) kat

text:
if a relationship consistantly makes you feel bad about yourself, you are in a toxic relationship.
.
the #1sign of emotional abuse is a diminished self-esteem and a feeling of worhlessness.
. 
a  victim of abuse might not even realize that his or her identity is slowly being destroyed.
.
one day you  just start thinking "i don't know who i am anymore? what happened to the vibrant happy person i once was? i feel so worthless"
.
abuse is a soul crusher! an identity thief, a sparkle extinguisher, a worthiness destroyer, a self concept confuser, a subtle but deadly killer of dreams and destinies.
.
if you or someone you love is in an abusive relationship please share this. even if someone is experiencing verbal or emotional abuse (the ones that go unnoticed and are far more damaging to the soul than physical abuse) let them know they need to tell someone and get help.
.
if that person is you. know this: you are not worthless, you are not alone. you are not stuck, and there is a way out.
.
#abuse #emotionalabuse #sexualabuse #verbalabuse #happiness #love #innerhealing #toxicrelationships #toxiclove #toxicrelationship #gethelp #metoo #selfworth #selfconcept #identity #youareenough #goodenough #selfesteem

text:
beaming in with the badness to remind you kingdoms are built together & humans are social creatures // as we rule the many kingdoms of this earth, as the royalty we are, we must remember to not be the foolish king who claimed they did it themselves. overlooking the kingdoms of farmers that grew the food that fueled his body, the kingdom of architecture that built his home, his general counsel though of few words who have kept him from madness, and many many many more. we each have a kingdom to care for be it, animals, a sector of technology, education, precious stones, medicine, fashun, or the all encompassing business. and if we are to continue to make a conscious effort towards shifting the waters of our actions as a human race from destruction we must not fool ourselves into thinking we ever did it alone. there is no pride in that. i stand taller knowing there are millions surrounding me and we act together. i am thankful for those i interact with more intimately who remind me of our greatness & hold me accountable to maintain that standard. we all need an epic journey of self into the wilderness every now and then, but eventually we return to each other and we must act accordingly with grace when we do. royalty is our birthright ğŸ™ğŸ¾ğŸ‘½ğŸ‘¾ğŸ‘¸ğŸ¿ğŸ‘¸ğŸ¾ğŸ‘¸ğŸ½ğŸ‘¸ğŸ¼ğŸ‘¸ğŸ»ğŸ¤´ğŸ¿ğŸ¤´ğŸ¾ğŸ¤´ğŸ½ğŸ¤´ğŸ¼ğŸ¤´ğŸ»

text:
vinta nanda speechless after alok nath cast as judge in upcoming #metoo-themed film, says itâ€™s ironical
#
mumbai: a news report that actor alok nath is playing a judge pronouncing a sentence against a child molester in a forthcoming film has left writer-director vinta nanda, who has accused him of rape, speechless. titled "#mainbhi", the film has been directed by nasir khan, said the report. "i don't know what to say. when i heard about this ironical casting my mind, my heart and soul was with wing commander varthaman abhinandan. i couldn't keep my eyes off the television screen because i wanted to see him as he stepped on indian soil today," vinta said emotionally. her mindspace is currently taken up with the violence at the border. "i'm praying for peace and wishing that the almighty grants us a non-violent universe. i can't think of anything else at the moment," she said. and she isn't bothered with what alok nath is doing. "this piece of news about alok nath acting in a film is irrelevant and has no effect upon what is actually going on in my heart," she said. vinta had accused alok nath of allegedly raping her nearly 19 years ago when they worked together, which made for several such claims about his behaviour onâ€¦

you do. you really, really do.... this is one helluva collection, a buffet of stories which grab you by your hair and pull you close, get you wanting what you're sure, from your past experiences, you'll certainly receive. and you'll get what you want and more. much more. you'll get and get until it's too much. that stoked lust takes you for all the fuel your worth. your heart beats itself tender, the sinew and gristle liquifies and gels, liquifies and gels. 
fucking great book. buy it. borrow it. read it. 
you've been warned.

text:
a couple nights ago i was in an uncrowded bar with my daughter picking up a take out order.  there were maybe 8 people total in the room.  i was startled when someone put his hand on my back and grabbed my arm, breathing "excuse me" into my hair.  i jumped out of my skin and swung around to face him, to which he seemed offended.  my gut reaction was to apologize but i stared blankly at him instead. .
.

at that point i realized how often in my life i have been impacted by varying degrees and versions of unwanted touch.  i was pissed.  i was worried for my daughter and do not want for her to ever become numb and accepting of unwanted touch. .
.

as a woman it has taken me most of my life to unlearn what i have been taught to be sorry for.  it is sickening and saddening.  therefore i write and will get comfortable speaking my truth. .
.

no sir, i did not overreact to your unwanted and uninvited touch.  no, i am not sorry that i startled you with my visceral response.  no,  sir it is not okay for you to touch my back to excuse yourself.  i hear you just fine without your hands on me. 
#loribrinkleycounseling #selflove #metoo #boundaries #useyourvoice #youarenotalone #mentalwellness

text:
have i ever mentioned i'm a soroptimist? actually, a member of soroptimist. it's a service club and the goal is to socially and economically empower girls and women. worldwide.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
this image is of a work in process that will benefit the club and all proceeds will go directly into the goal of empowerment.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
yesterday, i was being interviewed by a fellow glass artist (she's a writer and businesswoman on top of that.) and she asked me what would i say to encourage more women to enter the glass world.  my response was, i'm not sure i'd say anything. iâ€™m not so sure that people should be encouraged into glass based on gender.â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i've had the day to think it over, and here is what i would say to any woman to encourage her into the glass world:â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
"you have a voice. your voice is a vital part of the dialogue that is our culture. glass is an amazing medium which can be used to express that voice. if you think you can use glass, even in some small way, to accomplish that expression. . . join us. but glass is just one medium. and although i have found a voice in it there are so many other ways.  just please, whatever you do . . . find the medium that will express your voice, your point of view . .  and when you do . . . wield it like an unruly sword." â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
courtesy of the new york times, jason horowitz, elisabetta povoledo, &  nicholas kristof (articles available on pinterest)
two churches. same issue. same problem. and no it's not men. it's not even the clergy. it's privilege and entitlement. 
the vatican have admitting amidst allegations strengthened by the #metoo movement that they have contrived to cover up cases of rape and sexual misconduct between priests and disabled children and nuns. lately however they have admitted that there are secret rules for children fathered by clerics. 
southern baptist leaders are similarly indifferent to the spate of sexual assaults against women and underage girls by their all male clergy. underpinning this despite the open-ness in the preaching of jesus, is a very patriarchal interpretation of the bible. 
why do religious clergy insist on abstinence and to what does this offer women who seek piety in the throes of religious belief? #religion #abstinence #romancatholic #illegitimatechildren #southernbaptist #rape #molestation #abuse #clergy #allmaleclergy #newyorktimes #christianity #patriarchy

text:
#marymagdalene is often portrayed as the seductress, the sexual and therefore the one being connected to the earthy side of femininity. 
she carries a lot of stigma coming from sexuality and women being sexual without marriage and a partner. 
sheâ€™s been seen (and called) a prostitute and adulteress. 
and nowadays many still feel that stigma about being a woman and having sexual choices and freedom. and me too highlights the importance of these themes and itâ€™s time to start shifting through them as a society. 
many women are still judged.
many are not feeling sexually free. 
are not comfortable with their body. 
a lot carry trauma from suffering sexual abuse and been taking advantage of. 
there's dis-trust in sexuality. 
in the other sex. 
and towards themselves. 
many women still do not know how to get confident with sexuality, with equality and allowing themselves to be feminine and sexual and do what they do desire. 
mary magdalene followed her heart and faith and sacrificed for what she personally believed in.

it's not at all proven she was a prostitute. 
yet, she did surely carry (and received) that stigma. 
iâ€™ve noticed that many women feel a strong connection with this archetype and she can be extremely beneficial to start healing the self and experiences of sexual abuse or harassment with this.

the mary magdalene meditation will be given as a bonus to the sacred sexuality workshop. 
both are high energy clearings you can watch and work with in private: one with vows of abstinence  and releasing past experiences that may stand in the way. 
and mary magdalene assists with rebalancing the male and female power from within. 
the more i'm uploading all of this for you, the more i feel how incredibly important this is. not for society (even though all healing you do will have a ripple effect on society as a whole) but for yourself.

what occurred at the first event this week speaks to the power in unapologetic womxn facing extreme circumstances with our dear friend, jane, and why this body of work needs to be created.

our why: â €
the silence surrounding violence against womxn needs to end. we believe that cannabis can be both a bridge and a vessel in ending that silence. â €
â €
she helps the sexual-assault survivor find her words. she helps the little girl who lost her mom at 10, negotiate a lonely and obsessive world into her thirties. she helped the violent crime survivor leave her house again. â €
â €
so we tell our stories not only in homage to our personal & collective healing via plant medicine, but also to end the stigma against discussing the horrific things that happen to womxn all over this world every day. â €

text:
millions of people still lack the most basic human rights, with things like discrimination of women in the workplace, modern slavery, and anti-lbgt laws a reality for many. today, there are around 40 million victims of modern slavery worldwide, 42% of american women experience workplace discrimination, and in 2017 alone, nearly 130 anti-lgbt bills were introduced across the nation. fortunately, there are many competent organizations working to change these statistics by helping to protect and uphold the universal declaration of human rights.

free press, human rights first, human rights watch, and national womenâ€™s law center are simply virtuousâ€™ hand-picked, most influential charities fighting to ensure human rights for all. these non-profits are working to expose and combat the injustices in our world to ensure a better future for all. learn more about what they do at www.simplyvirtuous.org

text: in celebration of internation women's day next week i will be posting some cool facts for the week about what women have overcome. i used to be someone who thought it was unfair that there's a women's day but not a men's day. now i see what we celebrate for. often people would say things like "oh my general rule of thumb is...." well where this came from is the fact that a man could beat his wife with a stick the size of or smaller than his thumb. we think this seems like a long time ago but it really isn't. #believeher #metoo #domesticviolence #domesticviolencesurvivor #domesticviolenceawarness #emotionalabuse #verbalabuse #gaslighting #physicalabuse #icanpickmyselfup #bestrongerthan #internationalwomensday #womenempowerment #womensupportwomen

how alive its presence isâ€”
i eat now
go to work
sleep through the night
i drink now
hang with friends
laugh in spite
i hope now
exercise
lie down in peace
iâ€™m loving

til it extends its claws
and whips its tail
til it rises and rips
through the surface

til it roars and i writhe
til it beats and i bawl

then i remember
iâ€™ve been eating poorly
working without energy
sleeping through some nights

not trusting my friends

motivation has been waning

truthfullyâ€”iâ€™ll never forget.

text:
the problem with fake news isnâ€™t just fake news. it starts with you. it starts with the lack of fact checking, partisanship. there will be a point in life where you need to re-evaluate the quality of people around you as the saying by jim rohn goes:
â€œyou are the average of the five people you spend the most time with.â€
in addition, like what the law of attraction states: â€œyou attract who youâ€™re beingâ€. i made a mental note to observe and to listen carefully about what exactly are the people in my life talking about regularly and what was usually being discussed just between the both of us. i noticed that the people who speak with strong conviction, with sincerity, who see the good in others, in dire situations, are the ones who do not engage in gossip. they are the kind of people who do not bother too much about what others think of them, who see the good in everything and everyone regardless of the situation that they are in and of course, who are always beaming with joy and looking into the future with optimism. i want to be like them. happy, down-to-earth, forgiving, genuine, appreciative and kind-hearted.after all, life is meant to be lived to the fullest instead of caring way too much about the trivial matters- including mindless gossip.
***

text:
when itâ€™s ok to not give af during communication
.
when i think about language, unique words and phrases symbolic of a specific company or person instantly spring to mind. i define effective communication, as a way messages are designed to be perceived and experienced by the listener or reader  to achieve a specific goal.
.
businesses and public figures  use language and communication to distinguish themselves from competition all the time. this is branding, and in this context more specifically for small service businesses, the rules of general communication can be altered!
.
i've met quite a few business owners that has prospered on account find their way of saying things.
.
more specifically the client above, milky. she desired to brand this unique way she did nails. while there are a couple things to take into consideration when becoming the face of your brand or naming your brand after yourself etc, everything fitted perfectly for this client.
.
she had a unique name for one (yes milky is her really name) and she was doing something ground breaking in that, no one else was doing it. so branding it made sense.
.
what are some of the things you consider when you think about naming your brand or even becoming the face of your brand?
.

text:
it happens.

there will be people who don't understand what you're going through. i know this can feel discouraging, but try not to take it too personally. the ones who don't understand your journey have probably just been fortunate enough to have not been through anything similar to what you're going through. sometimes people respond poorly to what they don't understand. it can be hard for others to know what to say or do when they have no idea what it's like to go through what you're going through. for me personally, i've felt upset and honestly envious of those who don't understand my journey. they're blind to what it feels like, just like i used to be.

thinking about how fortunate they are to not know what it's like has also made me fall into a case of self-pity. i start asking questions that no one will ever have answers to; "why me?" "why couldn't i have stayed blind to knowing what it feels like to go through something as horrible as this?" but this is a dangerous path to allow your mind to go down, all it leads to is a deep dark pit that can be hard to climb out of. instead of allowing yourself to dwell too much on those who don't understand your journey and how you wish they did, take a deep breath and try your hardest to push those thoughts away. dwell instead on how blessed you are to have people who do understand your journey. the ones who do understand your journey will be there for you. we will always be here for you. we are in this together. 
stay strong, darling. you got this.

text:
imagine yourself at a restaurant with your family. you ordered a bottle of wine and youâ€™re waiting for the waitress to come back to your table and pouring the first sip of wine into somebodyâ€™s glass. have you noticed that the â€œoneâ€ having the pleasure to try it first changes according to people youâ€™re with?
as far as i know, if there is a man seated at the table, heâ€™s gonna be the one. in this case, the waitress doesnâ€™t even think twice before pouring it into his glass.
however, the question â€œwho would like to try itâ€ arises at a table of only women.
why? 
how blind are we to be unable to recognize that this episode is just an additional expression of male power or patriarchy (if we wanna be more precise)? the waitress sees the man at the table and immediately associates him to the idea of making decisions, money and, therefore, to the authority.
itâ€™s exactly these mental associations that must warn us that something is wrong.
the idea man-power is so deeply absorbed and metabolized in all of us that our actions are schematically carried on, without even thinking. these spontaneous associations or silent norms are nothing else than reflections of the society we are in and thatâ€™s why education or re-education becomes necessary as a mean of eradication of these apparently harmless actions.
of course, this was just an example of a patriarchal society that hides itself behind thoughts, actions and behaviours and most of the time these are even too subtle to be identified.
from this, the urge of being critical and analytical towards everyone and everything should become a moral and social duty, a paramount necessity that can no longer be ignored.

it's difficult choosing a favourite product to be honest, my realtionship with each product can vary, it depends on the day, my mental health, the quantity in an order, my backlog etc. i can love an item one day and hate making it the next. one of my bestsellers is currently not for sale for this exact reason!
.
today i'm inclined to say this tshirt i did for an order this week is one of my faves, as i always forget just how gorgeous that glitter is! ğŸ˜
.
i make all of my tshirts to order currently, so everytime i get an order i am reminded just how beautiful the teal and silver glitter combination is. isn't it just lush!? ğŸ–¤
.

text: here we go ladies!! daily poetry for you. i have been writing poetry for many years but was inspired when the #metoo movement started and during a nasty #divorce to create the herku. it is a spin off of the #haiku but has a 6-9-6 syllable format because us women have a lot more to say! i want to inspire women and encourage them to use their voices. we will not be silenced. we will not stay quiet. we will not let bad people get away with it. no more. it stops now. we women will uplift one another, help each other, stick together and fight the good fight and love with abandon. may we all spread our wings and soar to the highest heights and hear our soul sing!!! @metoomvmt @womensmarch @feministabulous @feminist @womensbest @bossbabe.inc @womenshealthmag @womenirl @girls_pride_ @females @femalepositivity @thefemaleclub @respect_women._ @oprah @gloriasteinem @officialhilaryclinton @beyonce @ellendegenneress @theellenshow @pink @the_real_iman @merylstreep @ruth.bader.ginsburg @michelleobama

text:
dennis graham, drake's father, spoke withÂ varietyÂ to promote his latest single "that on that." during the q&a, the outspoken graham discussed the recent controversies surrounding r. kelly andÂ empire's jussie smollett. graham defended the two, stating that they are his friends and he supports them no matter what. "heâ€™s a good friend of mine," said graham of r. kelly, who was charged with 10 counts of criminal aggravated sexual abuse last week (feb. 22). "i wish him the best. i hate that itâ€™s happening to him. thereâ€™s a reason why women come out after the fact. he has my support 100%." as for smollett, who is being accusedÂ of allegedly filing a false police report after claiming he was attacked by trump supporters in chicago, graham says that the actor and singer is just "misunderstood." "as a matter of fact, they know that," graham continues. "that story that came out about jussie in chicago is not true about jussie. jussie is a friend of mine, also. they have totally reconstructed his story." dennis graham has been no stranger to voicing his opinion on hot-button topics, such as the #metoo movement and pusha t's beef with his son. he also said that he had "no idea" what was going on regarding his son's child, adonis.

text:
as we transition from black history month to womenâ€™s history month, let us not forget to give recognition to the black women that are constantly fighting for us, yet most of the time forgotten or not given enough praise for all that they do. for fighting to protect us, to love us, to help us advance. 
a lot of times, womenâ€™s history month is used as a platform to showcase yt womenâ€™s history, letâ€™s stop that from happening this time around. 
shared from the page of @metooethiopia: â€œmeza ashenafi was appointed as head of ethiopiaâ€™s supreme court. before being appointed as head of ethiopiaâ€™s supreme court, ashenafi was a judge on ethiopiaâ€™s high court and an advisor to a commission that writes ethiopiaâ€™s constitution. because of her firm belief in representation, she founded the first ethiopian womanâ€™s lawyers association and contributed in the establishment of ethiopiaâ€™s first womenâ€™s bank: enat bank. from all of her important court cases, ashenafi is famously known for a case that banned kidnapped girls be forced into marriage. because of the attention her case received, it was turned into an ethiopian film called â€œdifretâ€. â€œdifretâ€ was executively produced by angelina jolie. although ashenafi helped to outlaw the tradition that causes kidnapped girls to be forced into marriage, problems similar to ashenafiâ€™s well-known case are still prevalent. across ethiopia, 41% of girls are married off as children and 16% of them before their 15th birthday. despite the change, abduction and forced marriage still occurs in ethiopia. to be in fact, in some southern parts of ethiopia, one in six girls are abducted into marriage.â€ thank you @metooethiopia for using your platform to shed light and bring awareness to issues that so many people here in the states have no idea about, and that so many people back home are too afraid to talk about. these stories are close to me because my grandmother was married off by the age of 13, as well as all of her sisters.
sign the petition to prevent girls being married at a young age. sign the petition to prove assault is a crime, not a culture. the link is in @metooethiopiaâ€™s bio. 
#metoo #metooethiopia  #blackhistory #ethiopianhistory

text:
i was a little overwhelmed this morning for the immense response that was given on facebook to the lost little girl posts. i wept as i read each comment and how survivors also identified themselves with the lost little girl. how many little girls and little boys are trapped and lost in the clutches of sexual abuse. how many more children's lives will be affected by this terrible crime? the next time you witness a child walking deep in thought or have fear in their eyes don't ask them what's wrong with you? because there is nothing wrong with us. something very wrong is happening to us. ask children what happened to you? are you okay? let me help you.  i'm here for you and i will protect you.

the lost little girl is now me...
she's no longer lost or hurting.

text: "awareness is the "there" that everyone wants to get to. most of the women i work with have a different notion what it means to be â€œdone.â€ they often have an idea in their mind of everlasting peace and happiness that will never be threatened, sullied or punctured. but life is unpredictable. life is a constant ebb and flow of uncertainty woven together with times of little to no control and little to no information. we can never stop our bodies from feeling uncomfortable but when we use our embodied resources to recognize that our bodies are responding to something, and understand that this response likely has more to do with a past memory than the current circumstance, we can use simple tools to help us navigate through the moment. this continues to build our confidence, our self-knowledge and our resilience. with practice you will find yourself acutely  aware of your own body sensations in the midst of a difficult conversation or moment with others. you will notice the thoughts in your mind, the things you would habitually say and the actions you habitually would take, all from a place of a higher observer. youâ€™ll be able to simply hold space for all of those things without acting on them and this will allow you to feel extremely empoweredâ€”especially if others around you are clearly lacking these skills and reacting from a place of stress reactivity." #relationshipgoals #wellbeing #metoo #men #yoga #trauma #traumarecovery ##healing #healing #community #authorsofinstagram #writersofinstagram #selfhelp #selflove #mindfulness #womenempowerment #woman #women

why the â€˜brooklyn nine-nineâ€™ #metoo episode is so effective
#
brooklyn nine-nine has always managed to skillfully tackle sensitive topics, and the nbc comedy's #metoo episode "he said, she said" that aired thursday night was no exception. the episode, directed by cast member stephanie beatriz, unpacked some of the micro aggressions women experience daily, along with the push and pull of the #metoo movement and why it won't be a quick or easy battle. not for the first time, tv comedy (brookyln in particular) carefully tackled a delicate subject without overlooking the subtleties within. black-ish did this brilliantly with 2016 election recap "lemons," and a recent superstore episode ("costume competition") unpacked cultural appropriation without sacrificing one drop of comedy. amy (melissa fumero) and jake (andy samberg) investigate a sexual assault allegation at a finance company. when the woman accusing her colleague (great news' briga wheelan) wants to take $2.5 million to stay quiet, amy convinces her to stand her ground while they pursue the case. from the very outset, "he said, she said" shows just how pervasive inappropriate behavior toward women is every day. a quick montage shows jake and amy going about their week with her experiencing unwanted touching on the subway and unnecessary comments from strangers ("you haveâ€¦
